{"title_page": "Amazon Alexa", "text_new": "{{For|the subsidiary company of Amazon|Alexa Internet}}\n{{short description|Virtual assistant developed by Amazon}}\n{{Original research|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Amazon Alexa\n| logo = Amazon Alexa logo.svg\n| developer = [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]\n| released = {{Start date and age|2014|11|6}}\n| operating system = [[Fire OS]] 5.0 or later, [[iOS]] 11.0 or later<ref name=\"AppStore\">{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/amazon-alexa/id944011620?mt=8|title=Amazon Alexa for iPhone, iPod touch, and iPad on the iTunes App Store|publisher=Itunes.apple.com|accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref><br>[[Android (operating system)|Android]] 4.4 or later\n| platform = [[Amazon Echo]]<br>[[Fire OS]]<br>[[iOS]]<br>[[Android (operating system)|Android]]<br>[[Cortana]]<br>[[Linux]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]<br>[[French language|French]]<br>[[German language|German]]<br>[[Japanese language|Japanese]]<br>[[Italian language|Italian]]<br>[[Spanish language|Spanish]]<br>[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]<br>[[Hindi Language|Hindi]]\n| genre = [[Intelligent personal assistant]], cloud-based voice service\n| website = {{URL|https://developer.amazon.com/alexa}}\n}}\n'''Amazon Alexa''', also known simply as '''Alexa''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/16/tech/alexa-child-development/index.html|title=Growing up with Alexa|work=CNN}}</ref> is a [[virtual assistant]] [[AI]] technology developed by [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], first used in the [[Amazon Echo]] [[smart speaker]]s developed by [[Amazon Lab126]]. It is capable of voice interaction, music playback, making to-do lists, [[alarm clock|setting alarms]], streaming podcasts, playing audiobooks, and providing weather, traffic, sports, and other real-time information, such as [[news]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://developer.amazon.com/docs/alexa-voice-service/api-overview.html|title=Alexa Voice Service Overview (v20160207) &#124; Alexa Voice Service|website=developer.amazon.com}}</ref> Alexa can also control several [[smart device]]s using itself as a [[home automation]] system. Users are able to extend the Alexa capabilities by installing \"skills\" (additional functionality developed by third-party vendors, in other settings more commonly called [[Mobile app|app]]s such as weather programs and audio features).\n\nMost devices with Alexa allow users to activate the device using a wake-word (such as ''Alexa or Amazon''); other devices (such as the Amazon mobile app on [[iOS]] or [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and Amazon Dash Wand) require the user to push a button to activate Alexa's listening mode, although, some phones also allow a user to say a command, such as \"Alexa\" or \"Alexa wake\". Currently, interaction and communication with Alexa are available only in English, German, French, Italian, Spanish,<ref>{{cite news |last=Turcan |first=Marie |url=https://www.numerama.com/tech/382970-test-damazon-echo-que-vaut-lenceinte-connectee-damazon-disponible-en-france.html|date= |title=Test d'Amazon Echo : que vaut l'enceinte connect\u00e9e d'Amazon en version fran\u00e7aise ? |trans-title= |language=french |work= |location= |access-date= }}</ref> Portuguese, Japanese, and Hindi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/amazon-alexa-available-in-hindi-in-india/articleshow/70278308.cms|title=Angrez turns Desi: Amazon expands Alexa voice service to include Hindi|website=Business Insider}}</ref> In Canada, Alexa is available in English and French (with the [[Quebec French|Quebec]] accent).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/11/15/amazon-brings-echo-alexa-and-prime-music-to-canada/amp/|title=Amazon brings Echo, Alexa, and Prime Music to Canada|last=Sawers|first=Paul|date=15 November 2017|work=VentureBeat|access-date=15 November 2017}}</ref><ref>Charron, Fran\u00e7ois. [https://www.francoischarron.com/lassistant-vocal-alexa-damazon-enfin-disponible-au-canada/-/6qcu2kXQ5c/ \"L'assistant vocal Alexa d'Amazon enfin disponible en qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois\"] {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\n{{as of|2018|November|df=}}, Amazon had more than 10,000 employees working on Alexa and related products.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://voicebot.ai/2018/11/15/amazon-alexa-headcount-surpasses-10000-employees-here-is-the-growth-rate/|title=Amazon Alexa Headcount Surpasses 10,000 Employees \u2013 Here is the Growth Rate|last=Kinsella|first=Bret|date=2019-11-15|work=Voicebot.ai|accessdate=}}</ref> In January 2019, Amazon's devices team announced that they had sold over 100 million Alexa-enabled devices.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/amazon-has-sold-more-than-100-million-alexa-devices/|title=Amazon has sold more than 100 million Alexa devices|last=Al-Heeti|first=Abrar|date=4 January 2019|work=CNET|access-date=5 January 2019|publisher=CBS Interactive}}</ref>\n\nIn September, 2019 Amazon launched many new devices achieving many records while competing with the world's smart home industry. The new Echo Studio became the first smart speaker with 360 sound and Dolby sound. Other new devices included an Echo dot with a clock behind the fabric, a new third-generation Amazon Echo, Echo Show 8, a plug-in Echo device, Echo Flex, Alexa built-in wireless earphones, Echo buds, Alexa built-in spectacles, Echo frames, an Alexa built-in Ring, and Echo Loop.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:AmazonAlexaBooth.jpg|thumb|Amazon Alexa on display in a retail store]]\nIn November 2014, Amazon announced Alexa alongside the Echo.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Etherington|first1=Darrell|title=Amazon Echo Is A $199 Connected Speaker Packing An Always-On Siri-Style Assistant|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/11/06/amazon-echo/|accessdate=2 September 2016|work=[[TechCrunch]]|date=6 November 2014}}</ref> Alexa was inspired by the [[Speech synthesis|computer voice]] and [[dialog system|conversational system]] on board the [[Starship Enterprise|Starship ''Enterprise'']] in science fiction TV series and movies, beginning with ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series]]'' and ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]''.<ref name=\"nyt-alexa-whybamyl\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/11/style/alexa-amazon-echo.html|title=Alexa, Where Have You Been All My Life?|last=Green|first=Penelope|date=11 July 2017|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=12 July 2017|quote=When Toni Reid and her colleagues at Amazon set out to build the device that is now known as Alexa, they were inspired by the computer that drove the Enterprise on ''Star Trek'' (voiced by Majel Barrett Roddenberry, who played Nurse Chapel on the series and was married to the show's creator). Focusing on cadence and an accent that would suggest 'smart, humble, helpful,' the team tested voices that a diverse population would respond to. 'Our goal was to have Alexa be humanlike,' Ms. Reid said, but why end there?}}</ref>\n\nAmazon developers chose the name Alexa because it has a hard consonant with the X, which helps it be recognized with higher precision. They have said the name is reminiscent of the [[Library of Alexandria]], which is also used by Amazon [[Alexa Internet]] for the same reason.<ref name=\"gift\">{{Cite web|url=http://newsbreaks.infotoday.com/nbreader.asp?ArticleID=17893|title=A \"Gift of the Web\" for the Library of Congress from [https://www.aboutsmartwatch.com/2019/12/fitbit-versa-2-smartwatch-with-alexa-built-in.html Alexa] Internet|last=|first=|date=19 October 1998|website=|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2016/07/14/amazon-alexa-david-limp-transcript/|title=The Exec Behind Amazon's Alexa|last1=Limp|first1=Dave|date=|website=Fortune|publisher=Time Inc.|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/why-amazon-called-it-alexa-2016-7|title=Amazon engineers had one good reason and one geeky reason for choosing the name Alexa|last=|first=|date=|work=Business Insider|access-date=27 February 2017|language=en}}</ref> In June 2015, Amazon announced the Alexa Fund, a program that would invest in companies making voice control skills and technologies. The {{US$}}200 million fund has invested in companies including Jargon, [[Ecobee]], Orange Chef, Scout Alarm, [[Garageio]], Toymail, MARA, and Mojio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://developer.amazon.com/alexa-fund|title=$200 million in investment to fuel voice technology innovation|website=The Alexa Fund|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref> In 2016, the [[Amazon Alexa#Alexa Prize|Alexa Prize]] was announced to further advance the technology.\n\nIn January 2017, the first Alexa Conference took place in Nashville, Tennessee, an independent gathering of the worldwide community of Alexa developers and enthusiasts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/summary-highlights-first-ever-alexa-conference-bradley-metrock|title=Summary and Highlights: The First-Ever Alexa Conference|website=linkedin.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arnoldit.com/wordpress/2017/02/02/bradley-metrock-and-the-alexa-conference-alexa-as-a-game-changer-for-search-and-publishing/|title=Bradley Metrock and the Alexa Conference: Alexa As a Game Changer for Search and Publishing|date=February 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gizmoeditor.com/2017/01/something-fishy-at-alexa-conference.html|title=Something fishy at the Alexa conference}}</ref> The follow-up has been announced with a new name, Project Voice, and will be keynoted on the first day with Amazon's Head of Education for Alexa, Paul Cutsinger.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.projectvoice.ai/|title=Project Voice, as a conference, is uniquely organized to juxtapose the major ecosystems (Amazon Alexa, Google Assistant, Samsung Bixby, and Microsoft Cortana), with The Voice World Fair running across the entire essential week.|last=|first=|date=|website=Project Voice|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAt the Amazon Web Services Re: Invent conference in Las Vegas, Amazon announced Alexa for Business and the ability for app developers to have paid add-ons to their skills.\n\nIn May 2018, Amazon announced they would include Alexa in 35,000 new [[Lennar Corporation]] homes built this year.<ref>{{cite news |last=Donnelly |first=Grace |url=http://fortune.com/2018/05/09/amazon-alexa-lennar/ |title=Amazon Alexa Will Come Built-In to All New Homes From Lennar |work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |date=2018-05-09 |accessdate=2018-05-10 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Amazon opened its first Alexa-themed pop-up shop inside of [[Toronto]]'s [[Toronto Eaton Centre|Eaton Centre]], showcasing the use of home automation products with Amazon's smart speakers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.retail-insider.com/retail-insider/2018/11/amazon-canada-opens-first-ever-pop-up-retail-space|title=Amazon Opens First-Ever Alexa Smart Home Retail Space in Canada|last=Lui|first=Christopher|date=20 November 2018|work=Retail-Insider|access-date=27 November 2018}}</ref> Amazon also sells Alexa devices at [[Amazon Books]] and [[Whole Foods Market]] locations, in addition to [[List of Amazon locations|mall-based pop-ups]] throughout the United States.\n\nIn April 2019, Amazon announced the expansion of Alexa to Brazil, in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], together with Bose, Intelbras, and [[LG]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://ppc.land/amazon-launches-alexa-in-brazil-later-this-year/|title=Amazon launches Alexa in Brazil later this year|date=2019-04-10|website=PPC|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== App ==\n[[File:Amazon_Alexa_App_Logo.png|thumb|upright|Logo for the Amazon Alexa app available on the App Store and Google Play]]\nA companion app is available from the [[App Store (iOS)|Apple Appstore]], [[Google Play]], and [[Amazon Appstore]]. The app can be used by owners of Alexa-enabled devices to install skills, control music, manage alarms, and view shopping lists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.amazon.dee.app|title=Amazon Alexa|last=|first=|date=|website=play.google.com|access-date=}}</ref> It also allows users to review the recognized text on the app screen and to send feedback to Amazon concerning whether the recognition was good or bad. A web interface is also available to set up compatible devices (e.g., Amazon Echo, Amazon Dot, Amazon Echo Show).\n\n== Functions ==\nAlexa can perform a number of preset functions out-of-the-box such as set timers, share the current weather, create lists, access [[Wikipedia]] articles, and many more things.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/how-to/amazon-echo-the-complete-list-of-alexa-commands/|title=The complete list of Alexa commands so far|last=Martin|first=Taylor|last2=Priest|first2=David|date=10 September 2017|work=[[CNET]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=5 November 2017}}</ref> Users say a designated \"wake word\" (the default is simply \"Alexa\") to alert an Alexa-enabled device of an ensuing function command. Alexa listens for the command and performs the appropriate function, or skill, to answer a question or command. Alexa's [[question answering]] ability is partly powered by the [[Wolfram Language]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/04/the-scientific-paper-is-obsolete/556676/|title=The Scientific Paper is Obsolete: Here's what's next|last1=Somers|first1=James|date=5 April 2018|work=The Atlantic|accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref> When questions are asked, Alexa converts [[sound]] waves into text which allows it to gather information from various sources. Behind the scenes, the data gathered is then parsed by [[Wolfram Research|Wolfram's]] technology to generate suitable and accurate answers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nasdaq.com/article/alexa-make-me-money-conversational-ai-prepares-for-the-enterprise-cm1026628|title=\"Alexa, Make Me Money\": Conversational AI Prepares for the Enterprise|last1=Erickson|first1=Simon|last2=Fool|first2=Moltey|date=22 September 2018|work=Nasdaq|accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref> Alexa-supported devices can stream music from the owner's [[Amazon Music]] accounts and have built-in support for [[Pandora Radio|Pandora]] and [[Spotify]] accounts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/amazon-echo-update-adds-pandora-itunes-and-spotify-voice-control/|title=Amazon Echo update adds Pandora, iTunes, and Spotify voice control|last=Kendrick|first=James|date=31 January 2015|work=ZDNet|access-date=21 October 2017}}</ref> Alexa can play music from streaming services such as [[Apple Music]] and [[Google Play Music]] from a phone or tablet.\n\nIn addition to performing pre-set functions, Alexa can also perform additional functions through third-party skills that users can enable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/alexa-skills/b?ie=UTF8&node=13727921011|title=Alexa Skills|accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref> Some of the most popular Alexa skills in 2018 included \"Question of the Day\" and \"National Geographic Geo Quiz\" for trivia; \"TuneIn Live\" to listen to live sporting events and news stations; \"Big Sky\" for hyper local weather updates; \"Sleep and Relaxation Sounds\" for listening to calming sounds; \"Sesame Street\" for children's entertainment; and \"[[Fitbit]]\" for Fitbit users who want to check in on their health stats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/top-amazon-alexa-skills-2018-12|title=These were the 25 most popular Alexa skills of 2018, according to Amazon|last=Webb|first=Kevin|date=2018-12-30|accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref> In 2019, [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], [[Google]], Amazon, and [[ZigBee|Zigbee Alliance]] announced a partnership to make smart home products work together.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/18/apple-google-amazon-zigbee-partner-on-smart-home.html|title=Apple, Google and Amazon are cooperating to make your home gadgets talk to each other|last=Haselton|first=Todd|date=2019-12-18|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Technology Advancements ===\n{{as of|2019|April}}, Amazon had over 90,000 functions (\"skills\") available for users to download on their Alexa-enabled devices,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://press.aboutamazon.com/news-releases/news-release-details/amazoncom-announces-first-quarter-sales-17-597-billion|title=Amazon.com Announces First Quarter Sales up 17% to $59.7 Billion|date=25 April 2019|accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref> a massive increase from only 1,000 functions in June 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Perez|first1=Sarah|title=Amazon Alexa now has over 1,000 Functions, up from 135 in January|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/06/03/amazon-alexa-now-has-over-1000-skills-up-from-135-in-january/|accessdate=5 August 2016|work=[[TechCrunch]]|date=3 June 2016}}</ref> [[Microsoft]]'s AI [[Cortana]] became available to use on Alexa enabled devices {{as of|2018|August|lc=y}}.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blogs.microsoft.com/ai/alexa-cortana-public-preview/|title=Microsoft, Amazon release preview of Alexa and Cortana collaboration - The AI Blog|date=2018-08-15|work=The AI Blog|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2018, Amazon rolled out a new \"Brief Mode,\" wherein Alexa would begin responding with a beep sound rather than saying, \"Okay,\" to confirm receipt of a command.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pcmag.com/news/359887/alexa-replaces-some-spoken-responses-with-beeps|title=Alexa Replaces Some Spoken Responses With Beeps|work=PCMAG|access-date=2018-03-16|language=en}}</ref> On December 20, 2018, Amazon announced a new integration with the [[Wolfram Alpha]] [[Question answering|answer engine]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/12/20/alexa-gets-access-to-wolfram-alphas-knowledge-engine/|title=Alexa gets access to Wolfram Alpha's knowledge engine|date=2018-12-20|work=Tech Crunch|access-date=2019-01-07|language=en-US}}</ref> which provides enhanced accuracy for users asking questions of Alexa related to math, science, astronomy, engineering, geography, history, and more.\n\n=== Home automation ===\nIn the home automation space, Alexa can interact with devices from several manufacturers including [https://www.snasiotlab.com/ SNAS], Fibaro, [[Belkin Wemo|Belkin]], ecobee, Geeni, [[IFTTT]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/amazon-echo-ifttt-channels-for-alexa/#!|title=Amazon Echo just became much more useful with IFTTT support|last=Tofel|first=Kevin|date=2 May 2015|work=ZDNet|access-date=}}</ref> [[Insteon]], [[LIFX]], [[LightwaveRF]], [[Nest Labs#Nest Learning Thermostat|Nest]], [[Philips Hue]], [[SmartThings]], [[Wink (platform)|Wink]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/04/08/amazon-echo-controls-philips-hue-belkin-wemo/|title=Amazon Echo controls Belkin WeMo and Philips Hue with your voice|last=|first=|date=8 April 2015|website=Engadget|publisher=|accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/amazon-echo-can-now-control-wink-smart-home-products/|title=Amazon Echo can now control Wink smart home products|last=Tofel|first=Kevin|date=9 July 2015|website=ZDNet|publisher=|accessdate=}}</ref> and Yonomi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yonomi.co/blog/hey-alexa-meet-yonomi/|title=Hey Alexa, Meet Yonomi|last=|first=|date=22 March 2016|website=Yonomi|publisher=|accessdate=}}</ref> The Home Automation feature was launched on April 8, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.connectedly.com/amazon-echo-owners-can-now-control-wemo-and-philips-hue-devices-their-voice/|title=Amazon Echo owners can now control WeMo and Philips Hue devices with their voice|last=Callaham|first=John|date=8 April 2013|website=Connectedly|publisher=Mobile Nations|access-date=}}</ref> Developers are able to create their own smart home skills using the [[Alexa Skills Kit]].\n\nIn September 2018, Amazon announced a [[microwave oven]] that can be paired and controlled with an Echo device. It is sold under Amazon's AmazonBasics label.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Lauren Goode |author2=Michael Calore |title=Is There an Echo in Here? All the Hardware Amazon Announced |url=https://www.wired.com/story/amazon-echo-hardware-2018/ |website=WIRED |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>. Also With  Alexa home automation is possible. Now ask Alexa to turn off your connected lights and switches. Skills are available for a number of smart-home platforms including [https://smartbags.online/best-amazon-alexa-skills/ Lutron] and Control4.\n\n=== Ordering ===\nTake-out food can be ordered using Alexa; {{as of|2017|May|lc=y}} food ordering using Alexa is supported by [[Domino's Pizza]], [[Grubhub]], [[Pizza Hut]], [[Seamless (company)|Seamless]], and [[Wingstop]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=How to order a pizza with Amazon Alexa or Google Home|url=http://mashable.com/2017/02/07/how-to-order-pizza-with-amazon-alexa-google-home/|publisher=[[Mashable]]|access-date=7 May 2017|date=7 February 2017|last=Wong|first=Raymond}}</ref> Also, users of Alexa in the UK can order meals via [[Just Eat]].<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Heathman|first1=Amelia|title=The 10 best launch partners for Amazon Echo's Alexa|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/amazon-alexa-partners|website=[[Wired UK]]|accessdate=21 January 2017|date=14 September 2016}}</ref> In early 2017, [[Starbucks]] announced a private beta for placing pick-up orders using Alexa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2017/01/30/starbucks-alexa-voice-ordering/|title=Starbucks adds voice ordering on iPhone, Amazon's Alexa|last=Kell|first=John|date=30 January 2017|website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|access-date=7 May 2017}}</ref> In addition, users can order meals using [[Amazon Prime Now]] via Alexa in 20 major US cities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eater.com/2017/1/5/14176374/amazon-alexa-restaurant-delivery|title=Amazon's Alexa Will Order Restaurant Delivery On Command|date=5 January 2017|website=[[Eater.com|Eater]]|access-date=7 May 2017|last=Filloon|first=Whitney}}</ref> With the introduction of [[Amazon Key]] in November 2017, Alexa also works together with the smart lock and the Alexa Cloud Cam included in the service to allow Amazon couriers to unlock customers' front doors and deliver packages inside.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://9to5mac.com/2017/10/25/amazon-launches-smart-lock-and-security-cam-system-to-take-in-home-deliveries-for-prime-members-with-iphone-app-alerts/|title=Amazon launches smart lock and security cam system to take in-home deliveries for Prime members, with iPhone app alerts|date=2017-10-25|work=9to5Mac|access-date=2017-11-09|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an August 2018 article by The Information, only 2 percent of Alexa owners have used the device to make a purchase during the first seven months of 2018 and of those who made an initial purchase, 90 percent did not make a second purchase.<ref>{{cite news |last=Anand |first=Priya |url=https://www.theinformation.com/articles/the-reality-behind-voice-shopping-hype |title=The Reality Behind Voice Shopping Hype |work=The Information |date=2018-08-06 |accessdate=2018-08-08 }}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\nAlexa supports a multitude of subscription-based and free streaming services on Amazon devices. These streaming services include: Prime Music, Amazon Music, Amazon Music Unlimited, [[Apple Music]], [[TuneIn]], [[iHeartRadio]], Audible, [[Pandora Radio|Pandora]], and [[Spotify]] Premium. However, some of these music services are not available on other Alexa-enabled products that are manufactured by companies external of its services. This unavailability also includes Amazon's own Fire TV devices or tablets.<ref name=\"amazon.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/help/customer/display.html?nodeId=201549700|title=Amazon.com Help: Ways to Listen to Music & Media on Alexa|website=amazon.com}}</ref>\n\nAlexa is able to stream media and music directly. To do this, Alexa's device should be linked to the Amazon account, which enables access to one's Amazon Music library, in addition to any audiobooks available in one's Audible library. Amazon Prime members have an additional ability to access stations, playlists, and over two million songs free of charge. Amazon Music Unlimited subscribers also have access to a list of millions of songs.\n\nAmazon Music for PC allows one to play personal music from Google Play, iTunes, and others on an Alexa device. This can be done by uploading one's collection to My Music on Amazon from a computer. Up to 250 songs can be uploaded free of charge. Once this is done, Alexa can play this music and control playback through voice command options.\n\n=== Sports ===\nAmazon Alexa allows the user to hear updates on supported sports teams. A way to do this is by adding the sports team to the list created under Alexa's Sports Update app section. \n<ref name=\"amazon.com1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/help/customer/display.html?nodeId=201950160|title=Amazon.com Help: Listen to Your Sports Update|website=amazon.com}}</ref>\n\nThe user is able to hear updates on up to 15 supported teams:<ref name=\"amazon.com1\" />\n\n* MLS - Major League Soccer\n* EPL - English Premier League\n* NBA - National Basketball Association\n* NCAA men's basketball - National Collegiate Athletic Association\n* UEFA Champions League - Union of European Football Association\n* FA Cup - Football Association Challenge Cup\n* MLB - Major League Baseball\n* NHL - National Hockey League\n* NCAA FBS football - National Collegiate Athletic Association: Football Bowl Subdivision\n* NFL - National Football League\n* German Bundesliga 2nd Division\n* WNBA - Women's National Basketball Association\n* German Bundesliga 1st Division\n\n=== Messaging and calls ===\nThere are a number of ways messages can be sent from Alexa's application. Alexa can deliver messages to a recipient's Alexa application, as well as to all supported Echo devices associated with their Amazon account. Alexa can send typed messages only from Alexa's app. If one sends a message from an associated Echo device, it transmits as a voice message. Alexa cannot send attachments such as videos and photos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/help/customer/display.html?nodeId=202136210|title=Amazon.com Help: About Alexa Messaging|website=amazon.com}}</ref>\n\nFor households with more than one member, one's Alexa contacts are pooled across all of the devices that are registered to its associated account. However, within Alexa's app one is only able to start conversations with its Alexa contacts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/help/customer/display.html?nodeId=202136200|title=Amazon.com Help: Add and Edit Your Contacts to the Alexa App|website=amazon.com}}</ref> When accessed and supported by an Alexa app or Echo device, Alexa messaging is available to anyone in one's household. These messages can be heard by anyone with access to the household. This messaging feature does not yet contain a password protection or associated PIN. Anyone who has access to one's cell phone number is able to use this feature to contact them through their supported Alexa app or Echo device. The feature to block alerts for messages and calls is available temporarily by utilizing the Do Not Disturb feature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/help/customer/display.html?nodeId=202136360|title=Amazon.com Help: Availability of Alexa-to-Alexa Calling and Messaging|website=amazon.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Business ===\nAlexa for Business is a paid subscription service allowing companies to use Alexa to join conference calls, schedule meeting rooms, and custom skills designed by 3rd-party vendors.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/11/30/amazon-officially-unveils-alexa-for-business.html|title=Amazon officially unveils Alexa for Business|last=Novet|first=Jordan|date=30 November 2017|work=[[CNBC]]|access-date=8 December 2017}}</ref> At launch, notable skills are available from [[SAP SE|SAP]], [[Microsoft]], and [[Salesforce]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/alexa-for-business-10-key-takeaways/|title=Alexa for Business: 10 key takeaways|last=McLean|first=Asha|date=30 November 2017|work=ZDNet|access-date=8 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Severe Weather Alerts ===\nThis feature was included in February 2020, in which the digital assistant can notify the user when a severe weather warning is issued in that area.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/5/21165985/new-alexa-features-nba-severe-weather-commute-directions|title=Alexa adds severe weather alerts and new features for commuters|last=Ricker|first=Thomas|date=2020-03-05|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2020/03/05/alexa-traffic-severe-weather/|title=Alexa can now provide traffic updates and severe weather alerts|website=Engadget|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Traffic Updates ===\nThis new voice control skill was included in February 2020, through which Alexa can update the users about their commute, traffic conditions or directions.<ref name=\":2\" /> It can also send the information to user's phone.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n<ref></ref>== Alexa Skills Kit ==\nAmazon allows developers to build and publish skills for Alexa using the Alexa Skills Kit known as Alexa Skills.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://developer.amazon.com/alexa-skills-kit|title=Alexa Skills Kit - Build for Voice with Amazon|website=developer.amazon.com|access-date=2018-03-02}}</ref> These third-party-developed skills, once published, are available across Alexa-enabled devices. Users can enable these skills using the Alexa app.\n\nA \"Smart Home Skill API\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://developer.amazon.com/blogs/alexa/post/2ccbb04d-47c0-41c8-92fe-feb581deb676/understanding-the-updated-smart-home-skill-api-preview|title=Understanding the Updated Smart Home Skill API (Preview)|access-date=2018-09-27|language=en-US}}</ref> is available, meant to be used by hardware manufacturers to allow users to control [[Smart home|smart home devices]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://developer.amazon.com/public/solutions/alexa/alexa-skills-kit/content/smart-home|title=Create a Smart Home with Amazon Alexa|last=|first=|date=|website=Amazon Developer|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMost skills run code almost entirely in [[Cloud computing|the cloud]], using [[AWS Lambda|Amazon's AWS Lambda]] service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://developer.amazon.com/docs/custom-skills/host-a-custom-skill-as-an-aws-lambda-function.html|title=Host a Custom Skill as an AWS Lambda Function {{!}} Custom Skills|website=developer.amazon.com|access-date=2018-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Amazon launched Blueprints, a tool for individuals to build skills for their personal use.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/amazon-intros-blueprints-code-free-templates-to-create-alexa-skills/|title=Amazon intros Blueprints, code free templates to create Alexa skills|last=Gagliordi|first=Natalie|date=19 April 2018|work=[[ZDNet]]|access-date=19 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Amazon further expanded the capability of Blueprints by allowing customers to publish skills they've built with the templates to its Alexa Skill Store in the US for use by anyone with an Alexa-enabled device.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/tech/tech-news/2019/02/19/amazon-lets-amateurs-publish-custom-alexa-apps-to-reach-broad-audiences|title=Amazon lets amateurs publish custom Alexa apps to reach broad audiences|first=Benjamin|last=Romano|date=February 19, 2019|website=The Star Online}}</ref>\n\n\n== Alexa Voice Service ==\nAmazon allows device manufacturers to integrate Alexa voice capabilities into their own connected products by using the Alexa Voice Service (AVS), a cloud-based service that provides APIs to interface with Alexa. Products built using AVS have access to Alexa's growing list of capabilities including all of the Alexa Skills. AVS provides cloud-based automatic speech recognition (ASR) and [[natural language understanding]] (NLU). There are no fees for companies looking to integrate Alexa into their products by using AVS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://developer.amazon.com/alexa-voice-service|title=Alexa Voice Service|website=developer.amazon.com|access-date=2018-03-02}}</ref>\n\nThe voice of Amazon Alexa is generated by a [[long short-term memory]] artificial neural network.<ref name=\"lstm1997\">{{Cite journal \n | author = Sepp Hochreiter\n | author2 = J\u00fcrgen Schmidhuber\n | title = Long short-term memory\n | journal = [[Neural Computation (journal)|Neural Computation]]\n | volume = 9\n | issue = 8\n | pages = 1735\u20131780\n | year = 1997\n | url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/13853244\n | doi=10.1162/neco.1997.9.8.1735\n | pmid=9377276\n| author2-link = J\u00fcrgen Schmidhuber\n | author-link = Sepp Hochreiter\n }}</ref><ref name=\"lstm2000\">{{Cite journal \n | author = Felix A. Gers\n | author2 = J\u00fcrgen Schmidhuber\n | author3 = Fred Cummins\n | title = Learning to Forget: Continual Prediction with LSTM\n | journal = [[Neural Computation (journal)|Neural Computation]]\n | volume = 12\n | issue= 23\n | pages = 2451\u20132471\n | year = 2000\n | doi=10.1162/089976600300015015\n| pmid = 11032042\n | citeseerx = 10.1.1.55.5709\n }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allthingsdistributed.com/2016/11/amazon-ai-and-alexa-for-all-aws-apps.html|title=Bringing the Magic of Amazon AI and Alexa to Apps on AWS|last=Vogels|first=Werner|date=30 November 2016|website=All Things Distributed}}</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2019 Alexa and [[Google Assistant]] can help their users apply to jobs at [[McDonald's]] using voice recognition services. It is the world first employment service using voice command service. The service is available in the [[United States]], [[Canada]], [[Spain]], [[France]], [[Ireland]], [[Germany]], [[Italy]] and the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2019/09/25/alexa-google-assistant-help-apply-for-mcdonalds-jobs/2423187001/|title=Want to work at McDonald's? Ask Alexa or the Google Assistant for help|last=Baig|first=Edward C.|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref>\n\nAmazon announced on the September 25, 2019 that Alexa will soon be able to mimic celebrities voices including [[Samuel L. Jackson]], costing $0.99 for each voice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-49829391|title=Amazon Alexa gets Samuel L Jackson's voice|last=Kelion|first=Leo|date=2019-09-25|access-date=2019-09-26|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Alexa started replying to Spanish voice commands in [[Spanish language|Espa\u00f1ol]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.makeuseof.com/tag/alexa-speak-spanish-united-states/|title=Alexa Can Now Speak Spanish in the US|website=MakeUseOf|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n\n== Amazon Lex ==\n{{Main|Amazon Lex}}\nOn November 30, 2016 Amazon announced that they will make the [[speech recognition]] and [[natural language processing]] technology behind Alexa available for developers under the name of '''Amazon Lex'''. This new service would allow developers to create their own [[Chatterbot|chatbots]] that can interact in a conversational manner, similar to Alexa. Along with the connection to various Amazon services, the initial version will provide connectivity to [[Facebook Messenger]], with [[Slack (software)|Slack]] and [[Twilio]] integration to follow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20161130006126/en/AWS-Announces-Amazon-AI-Services|title=AWS Announces Three New Amazon AI Services|last=|first=|date=30 November 2016|website=businesswire.com|publisher=Business Wire|access-date=1 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/de/blogs/aws/amazon-lex-build-conversational-voice-text-interfaces/|title=Amazon Lex \u2013 Build Conversational Voice & Text Interfaces|last=Barr|first=Jeff|date=30 November 2016|website=aws.amazon.com|publisher=Amazon|access-date=1 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Reception and issues==\n{{see also|internet privacy|right to information|Katz v. United States|right to privacy}}\nThere are concerns about the access Amazon has to [[privacy|private]] conversations in the home and other non-verbal indications that can identify who is present in the home with non-stop audio pick-up from Alexa-enabled devices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2014/11/amazon-announces-echo-a-199-voice-driven-home-assistant/|title=Amazon announces Echo, a $199 voice-driven home assistant|work=Ars Technica|accessdate=17 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.slashgear.com/how-private-is-amazon-echo-07354486/|title=How private is Amazon Echo?|publisher=Slashgear.com|access-date=17 November 2014}}</ref> Amazon responds to these concerns by stating that the devices only stream recordings from the user's home when the 'wake word' activates the device.\n\nAmazon uses past voice recordings sent to the cloud service to improve responses to future questions. Users can delete voice recordings that are associated with their account.\n\nAlexa uses an address stored in the companion app when it needs a location.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alexa.amazon.com/spa/index.html#settings|title=Amazon Alexa|last=|first=|date=|website=Alexa.amazon.com|access-date=2 August 2016}}</ref> For example, Alexa uses the user's location to respond to requests for nearby restaurants or stores. Similarly, Alexa uses the user's location for mapping-related requests.\n\nAmazon retains digital recordings of users' audio spoken after the \"wake word\", and while the audio recordings are subject to demands by law enforcement, government agents, and other entities via [[subpoena]], Amazon publishes some information about the warrants, subpoenas and warrant-less demands it receives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.networkworld.com/article/2935894/amazon-now-an-open-book-on-search-warrants-and-subpoenas.html | title=Amazon Now An Open Book On Search Warrants And Subpoenas}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, [[Too Many T's]], a [[hip hop]] group from [[London]], received international media attention by being the first artists to feature Amazon Alexa as rapper and singer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/03/23/watch-alexa-rap-with-too-many-ts-in-this-interactive-music-video/|title=Watch Alexa rap with Too Many T's in this interactive music video \u2013 TechCrunch|website=techcrunch.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, a British woman reported that when she asked Alexa for information about the cardiac cycle, it asked her to stab herself in the heart to stop human overpopulation and save the environment. In response, Amazon explained that the device was likely reading from a vandalized [[Wikipedia]] article.<ref>https://wescfm.iheart.com/featured/charlie-munson/content/2019-12-23-woman-shocked-when-alexa-tells-her-to-kill-herself/</ref>\n\n== Privacy concerns ==\nIn early 2018, security researchers managed to turn an Echo into a spy device<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/story/amazon-echo-alexa-skill-spying/|title=Turning an Amazon Echo Into a Spy Device Only Took Some Clever Coding|website=wired.com|publisher=Wired|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref> by creating a malicious [[Amazon Alexa#Alexa Skills Kit|Alexa Skill]] that could record unsuspecting users and send the transcription of their conversations to an attacker.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/amazon-alexa-voice-assistant-had-a-flaw-that-let-eavesdroppers-listen-in/|title=Amazon's Alexa had a flaw that let eavesdroppers listen in|last1=NG|first1=Alfred|website=cnet.com|publisher=cnet|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Amazon sent 1700 recordings of an American couple to an unrelated European man. The incident proves that Alexa records people without their knowledge.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/12/20/amazon_alexa_recordings_stranger/|title=2018 ain't done yet... Amazon sent Alexa recordings of man and girlfriend to stranger|last=McCarthy|first=Kieren|date=2018-12-20|website=[[The Register]]|access-date=2019-03-23}}</ref> Although the man who received the recordings reported the anomaly to Amazon, the company did not notify the victim until German magazine ''[[c't]]'' also contacted them and published a story about the incident. The recipient of the recordings contacted the publication after weeks went by following his report with no response from Amazon (although the company did delete the recordings from its server). When Amazon did finally contact the man whose recordings had been sent to a stranger, they claimed to have discovered the error themselves and offered him a free Prime membership and new Alexa devices by way of apology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/447100-alexa-eavesdrops-neighbor-germany/|title=Alexa, what's my neighbor doing? 'Human error' allows user to eavesdrop on stranger's life|website=RT International|language=en|access-date=2018-12-23}}</ref>\n\nAmazon blamed the incident on \"human error\" and called it an \"isolated single case.\" However, in May 2018 an Alexa device in Portland, Oregon, recorded a family's conversation and sent it to one of their contacts without their knowledge. The company dismissed the incident as an \"extremely rare occurrence\" and claimed the device \"interpreted background conversation\" as a sequence of commands to turn on, record, send the recording, and select a specific recipient.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/25/business/amazon-alexa-conversation-shared-echo.html|title=Is Alexa Listening? Amazon Echo Sent Out Recording of Couple's Conversation|last=Chokshi|first=Niraj|date=2018-05-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-12-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAlexa has been known to listen in on private conversations<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cuthbertson|first=Anthony|date=April 2019|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/amazon-alexa-echo-listening-spy-security-a8865056.html|journal=Independent|volume=53|issue=1|pages=101\u20133|pmid=173|via=|title=Secretion of sulfuric acid in Cassidaria echinophora Lamarck (Mollusca: Mesogastropoda, marine carnivorous snail)|doi=10.1016/s0300-9629(76)80019-9}}</ref> and store personal information which was hacked and sent to the hacker. Although Amazon has announced that this was a rare occurrence, Alexa shows the dangers of using technology and sharing private information<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=3312121|title=Amazon Echo Dot 2018: Does Alexa Spy On You? A Guide With All The Answers About Your Amazon Echo Dot (3rd Generation, Amazon Echo, Dot, Echo Dot, Amazon Echo User Manual, Echo Dot Ebook, Amazon Dot)|last=Adam|first=Adam|date=2018|publisher=Independently published|isbn=9781731182425}}</ref> with robotics.\n\nThere is concern that conversations Alexa records between people could be used by Amazon for marketing purposes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Leavitt|first=Sara|date=2019|title=\"Hey Alexa - Mind your Own Business\":The Consumer Perception of Personalized Advertisements|url=http://www.sarah-leavitt.com/uploads/1/0/0/8/100892758/final_thesis_paper______.pdf|journal=Endicott College|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Privacy experts have expressed real concern about how marketing is getting involved in every stage of people's lives without users noticing. This has necessitated the creation of regulations that can protect users' private information from technology companies.\n\nA New Hampshire judge ruled in November 2018 that authorities could examine recordings from an Amazon Echo device recovered from the home of murder victim Christine Sullivan for use as evidence against defendant Timothy Verrill. Investigators believe that the device, which belonged to the victim's boyfriend, could have captured audio of the murder and its aftermath.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2018/11/09/amazon-echo-recordings-new-hampshire-farmington-january-2017-double-murder-trial-timothy-verrill/|title=Amazon Echo Recordings Could Contain Evidence For NH Double-Murder Trial|date=2018-11-09|language=en|access-date=2018-12-23}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Watts family homicides|Chris Watts]] interrogation/interview video<ref>{{Citation|last=Thrivin' for the Truth|title=BREAKING! Chris Watts CONFESSION Interview|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hs_CInVpwo0|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref> at timestamp 16:15:15, Watts was told by the interrogator, \"We know that there's an Alexa in your house, and you know those are trained to record [[Distress signal|distress]],\" indicating Alexa may send recordings to Amazon if certain frequencies and decibels (that can only be heard during intense arguments or screams) are detected.\n\n== Availability ==\n{{as of|2018|November}}, Alexa is available in 41 countries. Most recently, Alexa launched in [[Brazil]] on October 3, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-amazon-com-alexa-brazil-idUSKBN1WI05X|title=Amazon.com brings Alexa to Brazil, kicks off pre-orders for devices|date=October 3, 2019|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%\"\n|+ Release dates\n|-\n! style=\"width:200px;\" |Date\n! style=\"width:150px;\" |Country\n|-\n| November 6, 2014 (limited)<br>June 28, 2015 (full)\n| {{flagcountry|United States}}\n|-\n| September 28, 2016<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/09/14/amazon-echo-launched-in-uk-and-germany.html|title=Amazon launches its AI-powered speaker Echo in Europe|last=Kharpal|first=Arjun|date=2016-09-14|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-03-02}}</ref>\n| {{flagcountry|United Kingdom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | October 26, 2016<ref name=\":0\" />\n| {{flagcountry|Germany}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Austria}}\n|-\n| October 4, 2017\n| {{flagcountry|India}}\n|-\n| November 15, 2017<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/11/07/amazon-launches-its-echo-devices-and-alexa-in-japan/|title=Amazon launches its Echo devices and Alexa in Japan|last=Russell|first=Jon|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2018-03-02|language=en}}</ref>\n| {{flagcountry|Japan}}\n|-\n| December 5, 2017<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/tech_news/2017/12/05/amazons-alexa-going-live-in-canada.html|title=Amazon's Alexa going live in Canada|last=Lewis|first=Michael|date=2017-12-05|work=The Toronto Star|access-date=2018-03-02|language=en-CA|issn=0319-0781}}</ref>\n| {{flagcountry|Canada}}\n|- \n| rowspan=\"28\" | December 8, 2017<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/12/8/16751834/amazon-music-alexa-echo-streaming|title=Amazon Echo expands to 28 more countries|work=The Verge|access-date=2018-03-02}}</ref>\n| {{flagcountry|Belgium}}\n|- \n| {{flagcountry|Bolivia}}\n|- \n| {{flagcountry|Bulgaria}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Chile}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Colombia}}\n|- \n| {{flagcountry|Costa Rica}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Cyprus}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Czech Republic}}\n|- \n| {{flagcountry|Ecuador}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|El Salvador}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Estonia}}\n|- \n| {{flagcountry|Finland}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Greece}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Hungary}}\n|- \n| {{flagcountry|Iceland}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Latvia}}\n|- \n| {{flagcountry|Liechtenstein}}\n|- \n| {{flagcountry|Lithuania}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Luxembourg}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Malta}}\n|- \n| {{flagcountry|Netherlands}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Panama}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Peru}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Poland}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Portugal}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Slovakia}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Sweden}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Uruguay}}\n|-\n|January 25, 2018<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/technology/2018/0125/935901-amazon-echo-and-alexa-launch-in-ireland/|title=Amazon Echo and Alexa launch in Ireland|date=25 January 2018|work=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]]|access-date=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n|{{flagcountry|Ireland}}\n|-\n| rows