{"title_page": "Francois Balloux", "text_new": "{{notability|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Balloux-pic.png|thumb|'''Francois Balloux''']]\n'''Francois Balloux''' is the Director of the UCL Genetic Institute,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/biosciences/departments/genetics-evolution-and-environment/research/ucl-genetics-institute|title=UCL Genetics Institute|last=UCL|date=2019-02-08|website=UCL Division of Biosciences|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and a Professor of Computational Systems Biology at [[University College London]].<ref name=\"ucl\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/biosciences/departments/genetics-evolution-and-environment/computational-biology-group/group-members/professor-francois-balloux|title=Professor Francois Balloux &#124; UCL Division of Biosciences - UCL - London's Global University|website=ucl.ac.uk|accessdate=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nHe earned a Master's degree in 1996 and a Doctorate in 2000 from the [[University of Lausanne]]. He then completed postdoctoral research at the [[University of Edinburgh]]. Balloux was a Lecturer at the [[University of Cambridge]], between 2002 and 2007, before taking a position as a Reader in Infectious Disease Epidemiology at [[Imperial College London]]. In 2012, Balloux became a Professor at [[University College London]].<ref name=\"ucl\"/>\n\nHis research lies at the interface of [[Genomics]], [[Epidemiology]], [[Evolution]] and [[Ecology]]. The main focus of his work is on the reconstruction of disease outbreaks and epidemics of human and wildlife [[Pathogen|pathogens]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Ruobing|last2=van Dorp|first2=Lucy|last3=Shaw|first3=Liam P.|last4=Bradley|first4=Phelim|last5=Wang|first5=Qi|last6=Wang|first6=Xiaojuan|last7=Jin|first7=Longyang|last8=Zhang|first8=Qing|last9=Liu|first9=Yuqing|last10=Rieux|first10=Adrien|last11=Dorai-Schneiders|first11=Thamarai|date=2018-03-21|title=The global distribution and spread of the mobilized colistin resistance gene mcr-1|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-018-03205-z|journal=Nature Communications|language=en|volume=9|issue=1|pages=1\u20139|doi=10.1038/s41467-018-03205-z|issn=2041-1723|pmc=PMC5862964|pmid=29563494}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=O\u2019Hanlon|first=Simon J.|last2=Rieux|first2=Adrien|last3=Farrer|first3=Rhys A.|last4=Rosa|first4=Gon\u00e7alo M.|last5=Waldman|first5=Bruce|last6=Bataille|first6=Arnaud|last7=Kosch|first7=Tiffany A.|last8=Murray|first8=Kris A.|last9=Brankovics|first9=Bal\u00e1zs|last10=Fumagalli|first10=Matteo|last11=Martin|first11=Michael D.|date=2018-05-11|title=Recent Asian origin of chytrid fungi causing global amphibian declines|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/lookup/doi/10.1126/science.aar1965|journal=Science|language=en|volume=360|issue=6389|pages=621\u2013627|doi=10.1126/science.aar1965|issn=0036-8075|pmc=PMC6311102|pmid=29748278}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Eldholm|first=Vegard|last2=Pettersson|first2=John H.-O.|last3=Brynildsrud|first3=Ola B.|last4=Kitchen|first4=Andrew|last5=Rasmussen|first5=Erik Michael|last6=Lillebaek|first6=Troels|last7=R\u00f8nning|first7=Janne O.|last8=Crudu|first8=Valeriu|last9=Mengshoel|first9=Anne Torunn|last10=Debech|first10=Nadia|last11=Alfsnes|first11=Kristian|date=2016-11-29|title=Armed conflict and population displacement as drivers of the evolution and dispersal of Mycobacterium tuberculosis|url=https://www.pnas.org/content/113/48/13881|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=113|issue=48|pages=13881\u201313886|doi=10.1073/pnas.1611283113|issn=0027-8424|pmc=PMC5137683|pmid=27872285}}</ref> and the emergence of [[antimicrobial resistance]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Balloux|first=Francois|last2=Br\u00f8nstad Brynildsrud|first2=Ola|last3=van Dorp|first3=Lucy|last4=Shaw|first4=Liam P.|last5=Chen|first5=Hongbin|last6=Harris|first6=Kathryn A.|last7=Wang|first7=Hui|last8=Eldholm|first8=Vegard|date=2018|title=From Theory to Practice: Translating Whole-Genome Sequencing (WGS) into the Clinic|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0966842X18301768|journal=Trends in Microbiology|language=en|volume=26|issue=12|pages=1035\u20131048|doi=10.1016/j.tim.2018.08.004|pmc=PMC6249990|pmid=30193960|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shaw|first=Liam P.|last2=Bassam|first2=Hassan|last3=Barnes|first3=Chris P.|last4=Walker|first4=A. Sarah|last5=Klein|first5=Nigel|last6=Balloux|first6=Francois|date=2019|title=Modelling microbiome recovery after antibiotics using a stability landscape framework|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41396-019-0392-1|journal=The ISME Journal|language=en|volume=13|issue=7|pages=1845\u20131856|doi=10.1038/s41396-019-0392-1|issn=1751-7370|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Eldholm|first=Vegard|last2=Rieux|first2=Adrien|last3=Monteserin|first3=Johana|last4=Lopez|first4=Julia Montana|last5=Palmero|first5=Domingo|last6=Lopez|first6=Beatriz|last7=Ritacco|first7=Viviana|last8=Didelot|first8=Xavier|last9=Balloux|first9=Francois|date=2016-08-09|editor-last=Jit|editor-first=Mark|title=Impact of HIV co-infection on the evolution and transmission of multidrug-resistant tuberculosis|url=https://doi.org/10.7554/eLife.16644|journal=eLife|volume=5|pages=e16644|doi=10.7554/eLife.16644|issn=2050-084X}}</ref> His work has been cited over 20,000 times on [[Google Scholar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.co.uk/citations?user=AwppHXYAAAAJ&hl=en|title=Francois Balloux - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>  \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Francois_Balloux|title=Francois BALLOUX &#124; University College London, London &#124; UCL &#124; UCL Genetics Institute (UGI)|website=researchgate.net|accessdate=2020-03-15}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://ucl.academia.edu/FrancoisBalloux|title=Francois Balloux &#124; University College London|website=Academia.edu|accessdate=2020-03-15}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balloux, Francois}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Academics of University College London]]\n[[Category:University of Lausanne alumni]]\n[[Category:Academics of Imperial College London]]\n[[Category:Computational biologists]]\n[[Category:21st-century biologists]]\n\n\n{{biologist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{notability|date=April 2020}}\n'''Francois Balloux''' is the Director of the UCL Genetic Institute,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/biosciences/departments/genetics-evolution-and-environment/research/ucl-genetics-institute|title=UCL Genetics Institute|last=UCL|date=2019-02-08|website=UCL Division of Biosciences|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and a Professor of Computational Systems Biology at [[University College London]].<ref name=\"ucl\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/biosciences/departments/genetics-evolution-and-environment/computational-biology-group/group-members/professor-francois-balloux|title=Professor Francois Balloux &#124; UCL Division of Biosciences - UCL - London's Global University|website=ucl.ac.uk|accessdate=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nHe earned a Master's degree in 1996 and a Doctorate in 2000 from the [[University of Lausanne]]. He then completed postdoctoral research at the [[University of Edinburgh]]. Balloux was a Lecturer at the [[University of Cambridge]], between 2002 and 2007, before taking a position as a Reader in Infectious Disease Epidemiology at [[Imperial College London]]. In 2012, Balloux became a Professor at [[University College London]].<ref name=\"ucl\"/>\n\nHis research lies at the interface of [[Genomics]], [[Epidemiology]], [[Evolution]] and [[Ecology]]. The main focus of his work is on the reconstruction of disease outbreaks and epidemics of human and wildlife [[Pathogen|pathogens]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Ruobing|last2=van Dorp|first2=Lucy|last3=Shaw|first3=Liam P.|last4=Bradley|first4=Phelim|last5=Wang|first5=Qi|last6=Wang|first6=Xiaojuan|last7=Jin|first7=Longyang|last8=Zhang|first